data.content:
Remove the `[ExpectedException]` attribute and wrap the throwing call in `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(
        () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));
}
```

**Why this is better:**
- **Precision** — `[ExpectedException]` catches exceptions from *any* line in the test, including the arrange step. `Assert.ThrowsExactly` targets the exact call.
- **Additional assertions** — you can capture the result to inspect the message:
  ```csharp
  var ex = Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(
      () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));
  Assert.AreEqual("email", ex.ParamName);
  ```

> **Note:** `Assert.ThrowsExactly` requires **MSTest v3.3+**. In older versions, use `Assert.ThrowsException<T>` (which behaves similarly but was renamed for clarity in newer MSTest). In MSTest v4, `[ExpectedException]` has been removed entirely.
